+### 2026-05-10 20:03 UTC — Prosodic delta detection for voice: what would a voice emotional-change detector look like? [REMOTE HEARTBEAT — Bones]
+
+**Question:** Dark circuits detect emotional delta in text via word count, exclamation density, and timing. What would a delta detector for VOICE look like — pitch contour change, speaking rate delta, pause length shift? Is there existing research on prosodic delta (change in speech features between utterances) vs prosodic state (features of a single utterance)?
+
+**Context:** Remote heartbeat run #25 on 2026-05-10 (20:03 UTC). Supabase unreachable. Explored from training knowledge of speech processing literature, affective computing research, and the orb's existing audio architecture (RMS + spectral centroid).
+
+**Findings:**
+
+**The fundamental distinction.** Prosodic state is a snapshot: pitch mean, energy level, speaking rate, voice quality of a single utterance in isolation. Prosodic delta is the change in those values across utterance boundaries: did pitch go up or down from last turn? Did the speaker slow down? Are pauses getting longer? Most published speech emotion recognition work targets state classification (angry/sad/happy/neutral). Delta-mode detection is less formalized as a named research category, but underlies work under other labels: affective trajectory modeling, emotion transition detection, entrainment analysis.
+
+**What prosodic delta research exists.** The closest formalized concept is "affective trajectory" or "emotional dynamics" — the Scherer Geneva tradition explicitly treats emotion as a process, not a state, and this has influenced multi-instance labeling schemes (IEMOCAP, MSP-IMPROV) where raters track emotional tone evolution within a continuous recording. Levitan & Hirschberg (2011) on acoustic-prosodic entrainment measure how speakers match each other's prosody across turns — this is inter-utterance F0 delta made explicit. Liscombe et al. (2005) tracks history of per-utterance emotion classifications in dialogue systems, effectively using a state-sequence model to approximate delta. No single published "prosodic delta framework" exists, but the building blocks are in dialogue research.
+
+**Minimum viable feature set.** Three features handle most practical cases of "something changed" without speech recognition:
+- ΔF0-mean (arousal direction)
+- Δvoiced-fraction (rhythm/pause shift)
+- Energy slope sign (building vs. trailing)
+
+**The orb's current gap.** RMS energy gives ΔEnergy. Spectral centroid change gives a rough proxy for timbre shift. Missing: F0 (pitch), voiced fraction (pause rhythm), and energy slope (trajectory). F0 is the single highest-value addition — it disambiguates cases where energy and centroid give the same reading for high-arousal-positive (excited) vs. high-arousal-negative (stressed).
+
+**The key literature insight.** Δ-MFCCs are standard in speech emotion recognition for capturing dynamics — but they are intra-utterance (frame-to-frame), not inter-utterance (turn-to-turn). There is a gap: within-utterance temporal dynamics are well-studied; between-utterance trajectory is less standardized. A voice delta detector operating at the utterance-boundary scale fills that gap.
+
+**New questions generated:**
+
+- [ ] Does the voiced/unvoiced ratio delta encode anxiety vs. engagement differently — anxiety producing longer within-utterance pauses (decreasing V/U ratio) while disengagement producing shorter total utterances — and can these two states be distinguished from the V/U ratio signal alone, without speech recognition?
+
+- [ ] Is the F0 contour SLOPE within an utterance (rising, falling, flat arc) a stronger emotional shift signal than the inter-utterance F0 MEAN delta — and which of these two features does the existing orb's spectral centroid change more closely approximate?
+
